The most likely cause is that **`BindingContext` is never set** on the page. The `{Binding}` markup works, but it has no source object to pull values from.

**Fix — set the BindingContext**, either in code-behind:

```csharp
public MyPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = new MyViewModel();
}
```

or in XAML:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:MyApp.ViewModels"
             ...>
    <ContentPage.BindingContext>
        <vm:MyViewModel />
    </ContentPage.BindingContext>
    ...
</ContentPage>
```

**Also verify** your ViewModel raises `PropertyChanged` so the UI updates when values change:

```csharp
public class MyViewModel : INotifyPropertyChanged
{
    public event PropertyChangedEventHandler? PropertyChanged;

    private string _title = "Hello";
    public string Title
    {
        get => _title;
        set { _title = value; PropertyChanged?.Invoke(this, new(nameof(Title))); }
    }
}
```

> **Tip:** The MVVM Community Toolkit's `ObservableObject` base class and `[ObservableProperty]` attribute eliminate this boilerplate.
